Please review:
@subutai @scottpurdy

…any of accept

Let me explain why I'm making this change. I have an endpoint that I want to return an image like so:
```
@app.route('/sp', methods=['GET'], cors=cors_config)
def pixel():
    return Response(PNG_PIXEL_DATA, headers={
        'Content-Type': 'image/png'
    })
```
This will be embedded in a webpage like `<img src='http://localhost:8000/sp' \>`. However, a browser (like Chrome) won't send the Accept header "image/png", it will send something like `Accept:image/webp,image/apng,image/*,*/*;q=0.8`. Chalice doesn't call this a match and throws out a 400. This is my attempt to fix this so that `Accept: image/*` will match `Content-Type: image/png`. I know this PR has no tests, but I wanted to see if this was an acceptable solution before writing any tests. Please gimme feedback (especially if this behavior exists due to some API Gateway behavior as I've only tested this via chalice local)!

Suggested by https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/issues/484#issuecomment-359508990

This will look in `notebook.json` in `~/.jupyter/nbconfig/notebook.json` for a `last_modified_buffer` value. For example:

```json
{
  "Notebook": {
    "Header": false,
    "Toolbar": true
  },
  "Cell": {
    "cm_config": {
      "lineNumbers": false
    }
  },
  "last_modified_buffer": 600
}
```

Can anyone think of better name than `last_modified_buffer`?

This patch allows to return [] in glob section:

```yaml
outputs:
  - id: "#indices"
    type: ["null",File]
    outputBinding:
      glob: |
          ${
            if (inputs.runMode == "genomeGenerate")
              return inputs.genomeDir+"/Genome";
            return [];
          }

```

GetAddressEntry() should return NULL when trying to get an invalid entry;
AppendChlidAddress() should only append valid addresses.
Hi @jwhui , could you help to have a review?

@pde had some stylistic concerns around #5639 which this PR addresses. I updated the docstring and split some of the code into a separate function. Rather making the code look something like:
```
if certname:
    new_name = certname
else:
    new_name = _strip_wildcard(domains[0])
...
def _strip_wildcard(domain):
    return domain[2:] if util.is_wildcard_domain(domains) else domain
```
I further split up the function moving the logical piece of determining the name for the lineage into its own function. This splits up `obtain_and_enroll_certificate` even more and better documents at a high level what is being done.

NPM and some other packages (including read-package-json that
@pulumi/pulumi) uses require the version field to be a valid
semver. So ensure ours are.
